  "local_port": 58360,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I am using a Moto G, and it failed to download the OTA update of Android due to a network error. Now what can I do to get it updated?",
  "response": "If your Moto G failed to download the OTA (over-the-air) update due to a network error, you can try the following steps to resolve the issue and get your phone updated:\n\n1. **Check Your Internet Connection**:\n   - Ensure you are connected to a stable Wi-Fi network.\n   - If possible, try switching to a different Wi-Fi network or using mobile data to download the update.\n\n2. **Restart Your Device**:\n   - Sometimes, a simple restart can resolve temporary issues with the device. Turn off your phone completely and then turn it back on.\n\n3. **Clear Cache of the System Update App**:\n   - Go to **Settings** > **Apps & notifications** > **See all apps**.\n   - Find and tap on the **Google Services Framework** or **System Update** app.\n   - Tap on **Storage & cache**, and then select **Clear cache**. \n   - Restart your phone and check for updates again.\n\n4. **Check for System Updates**:\n   - Go to **Settings** > **System** > **Advanced** > **System update**.\n   - Tap on **Check for update** and see if it allows you to download the update.\n\n5. **Free Up Space**:\n   - Ensure that you have enough free space for the update. Update files can be large, so check your storage under **Settings** > **Storage** and delete unnecessary files/apps to free up space if needed.\n\n6. **Boot into Safe Mode**:\n   - Booting into Safe Mode can help identify if third-party apps are causing issues. To boot into Safe Mode, press and hold the power button until you see the power off option, then tap and hold the \"Power off\" option until you see the \"Reboot to safe mode\" prompt. Tap \"OK\" to confirm.\n   - Check for updates in Safe Mode.\n\n7. **Factory Reset (Last Resort)**:\n   - If none of the above steps work, you may consider performing a factory reset. Note that this will erase all data on your device, so be sure to back up important data first.\n   - Go to **Settings** > **System** > **Reset options** > **Erase all data (factory reset)**.\n\n8. **Use ADB to Manually Update**:\n   - If you are comfortable with using ADB (Android Debug Bridge), you can download the factory images or OTA files for your device and use ADB to sideload the update. This is a more advanced method and should be done with caution.\n\n9. **Consult Motorola Support**:\n   - If you're still having issues, it might be best to contact Motorola's customer support for more assistance.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to resolve the update issue on your Moto G.",
